    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:53e799d0-46bd-4fd8-84f8-da35f1b1384b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 35-year-old Czech male who works as a software developer in Brno, spending long hours at a desk in front of multiple monitors. He is of average build, slightly overweight, with a pale complexion and mild yellowing of the sclera noted on examination. He presents with a several-week history of fatigue, right upper quadrant discomfort, and episodic nausea. He reports a sensation of abdominal heaviness that worsens after heavy meals or alcohol consumption [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:4].\n\n{patientName} has a busy but largely sedentary lifestyle. After work he typically unwinds with friends at local pubs, consuming approximately 3–4 beers most evenings. He is single, lives alone in a flat, and relies heavily on fast food and takeaways. His hobbies include gaming, cycling occasionally on weekends, and following Czech football. He has a close circle of friends from university but admits his social life revolves largely around alcohol [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:1].\n\nOn physical examination, {patientName} appears mildly icteric. His abdomen is soft but tender on deep palpation in the right upper quadrant, and the liver edge is palpable approximately 2 cm below the right costal margin, suggesting mild hepatomegaly [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:3]. No spider naevi or palmar erythema are noted. He denies any episodes of bleeding, altered consciousness, or inability to tolerate oral intake [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:2].\n\n{patientName} expresses concern about his abnormal liver function tests, which were incidentally found during a recent employer health check. He is anxious but cooperative, and motivated to reduce alcohol intake following the consultation. He denies use of illicit drugs and takes no regular prescription medications. He occasionally uses over-the-counter analgesics for headaches."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a349ccac-4556-493a-b8a4-7f082dc28d86",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior hospitalizations and no known chronic diseases. He does not have diabetes, hypertension, or known cardiac disease. He has no history of viral hepatitis diagnosis, though this has not previously been formally tested [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:3]. He underwent a gastroscopy approximately two years ago for epigastric complaints, which showed mild gastritis; he completed a short course of antibiotics at that time [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:5]. He has been taking omeprazole intermittently since then for acid reflux symptoms [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:5].\n\n{patientName}'s primary lifestyle risk factor is regular, significant alcohol use of approximately 20–28 units per week [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:1]. He is a non-smoker. His BMI is 27.4 kg/m², placing him in the overweight range. There is a family history of cardiac disease on his father's side [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:1]. His employer's occupational health check flagged elevated SGPT (ALT: 148.5 IU/L) and SGOT (AST: 93.8 IU/L), with serum bilirubin within high-normal range [MEDDIALOG:K75.9:4], prompting referral to a gastroenterology/hepatology outpatient clinic."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
